<font color="#FF0000">TO ARTHUR</font><br>
<tt>Mon Feb 17 16:28:10 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To Arthur<br>
As a fellow vet, and more importantly, as your friend, it grieves me and causes me distress that I have not been able to come up with anything that helps you with the amnesty issue.  I have not abandoned you to the bush, but I don't know why this seems not to be an issue with me as we probably have many parallel issues.  I have been wracking my brain trying to come up with something for you.  Let me throw some things out and see if they help.<br><br>
Just prior, during, and just after the release of the POW's from Vietnam, there was a brief discussion of whether or not some of these POW's should be court-martialed for their complicity in providing the NVA's with military information. This discussion was resolved by understanding that 1. that the war was over, there would not have been any &quot;gain&quot; by the prosecution of these men and 2. that whatever these men did, they did so to keep themselves and their fellow prisoners alive and 3. there were no doubts as to the methods used by the captors to extract information from these men.  How can anyone fault someone for releasing information under these conditions?<br>
Understanding the above, there could be those who insist that the information given by some of the POWs to our enemies did cause the lives of others in the war effort.  Maybe some of yours and my buddies.  If one accepts this argument, does this invalidate the arguments above?<br>
I don't think there are many, if any, that would hold any anger towards the POW's for what they needed to do to survive.<br><br>
I say all of this not to equat the survival of the POW's with what the draft evaders did.  The issues of these two groups are worlds apart.<br><br>
Dr Spatz re-iterated that our government abandoned us DURING the war and you agreed.  I also contend that the government abandoned us AFTER the war as well, and I'm sure there are not many that would disagree.  Is it just possible that Tom Dier was correct that the anger you feel is misplaced in the content that anything the government did then was to fuck over us vets?  I don't think there is a connection between the two.  I may be mistaken, but I don't think the government went out of their way to fuck us over after Nam, they just didn't do anything to help.<br><br>
Just something to think about.  E-mail me whenever you want.
<p><code>-- docdel@maui.net  (Doc Del) </code><p>


